{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_protoss_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280656306/1908062701/0508.xml":{"full_text":"V\\>^pt?i\nI I BR, ^r l||'\nADDITION TO COSMOS CI\nDCAI CCTATC MCQIDb\nIILnL LdlHIL UUuull\n7 ?_ J a\nGroup Plan of Designing City I\nHouses Described. I\n1 t\n_________ g\nLOCAL BUILDING ACTIVITY\nj i\nMore Buildings Going Up Than in J\nthe Early Months. c\ni\nIMPROVEMENTS IN PROGRESS I\nt\nt\nInfluence cf Lower Prices in the t\n1 P\nBuilding Trades Causing Unusual i A\nc\nVolume of Business. t\n6\nAn opportunity is seldom presented to an\narchitect, especially In designing city\nhouses of independent grouping. At the; r\nbest in the case of a building to be I t\nerected in a residence section of a\ncity the utmost that can be looked forward\nto is furnishing a front that is harmonious\nin itself, but which may be more 6\nor less affected by the surroundings en- n\ntirely beyond the control of the architect.\nThe city residence standing by itself and c\nwith its own setting is rarely to be n\nfound, so that a design which otherwise Y\nis effective is impaired by what is about is\nit and which coming from various hands 1\nand without thought of associating results 1\nin a grouping which may be lacking In\nunity or harmony, either in form or In\ncolor. t\nA Group of Houses. b\nThese conditions which are so common c\nh\nwith arcmtects or city nouses are not to\nbe found in the case of the designing of a\ntwo residences which is being done by 1:\nHill Kendal!, architects. The site se- b\ncured comprises the whole of a triangular\npiece of ground formed by the intersec- j 0\ntion of a transverse avenue with rectan- a\nguiar streets. The ground is bounded by\nS street. Phelps place and Florida avenue, i c\nJust west of Connecticut avenue and with r\na wide plaza to the east overlooking tne 1\nlatter avenue.\nThe long front of the ground is on S\nstreet, which is also the north exposure,\nand on that accounr is to be treated as\ninferior, not architecturally but in the interior\narrangement of the two houses that 1\nare to occupy this site. The western r\nportion of the ground is to be occupied h\nwith a house designed for Mr. Runyon. r\nwhile on the eastern section will be the ij\nhome of Mr. Heath. e\nColonial and French.\nThe former will be built of brick with s\nwhitejoints and with stone of light shade t\nand the woodwork finished in the same\ncolor and will be a long low structure, two\nstories in height and colonial in design, c\nThe other house will have the main en- d\ntrance at the corner of Florida avenue 8\nand S street and will be treated in the\nFrench style, the material used in the 0\nexterior being brick and stone of a light s\ncolor.\nIn the cas? of the latter house there will\nbe a circular entrance hall with access to 1\nth<. a in* U i I. ill I. i_ x r\nv\"*: oia?i^ooc, im ji v>im uv id liic crljufr,\nwith the landing on the main floor in a\nhall opening Into the suite of rooms\nwhich will have an unbroken sweep\nthrough the entire depth of the house of\nabout eighty feet.\nSouthern Exposure.\nIn the interior of the house as well as\nthat of the adjoining one the architects\nhave given to the principal rooms the ad- I\nvantage of the southern exposure, so that\nIn this paiticular the main portion fronts\non Phelps place. In the case of the most\nwes-tern house the main entrance is into a\nvestibule from which on either 3ide are i\ndoors opening into rooms which can he\nused as cloak rooms. The main door of\nthe house opens into a hall *r~m which\naccess is had to the suite of rooms that i\noccupy the entire southern front, a stretch\nof over sixty feet.\nLocal Building Situation.\nPersons who converse w?th architects\nand builders these days. and. of course,\non the topic of building, are informed\nthat the cost is much less at present\nthan it has been. In other words, the\nword has gone out that now is a good\ntime to put money in brick and mortar.\nThere seems to be no question in the\nmind of any one who is familiar with\nthe situation that more can be done\nwith money in this line now than at\nany- time for a number of years past.\nThe prospect from this point of view\naiore !s without a cloud There is no\ndoubv or Uiit.ci'iaitity. 1 iio only ^Uuii*\nflcation heard is \"Tf you l ave the i\nmoney.\" It is that lack that ails the\n1-ui.ii market just t.ow more than I\nany o'.ner ore thing. Whv there should\nbe such a lack, especially w.ih con.lt-\ntions as they are. is a quest-,on of much\nbroader scope than the building market\nor even the realty market. To find tne\n^^^^uiiiw?r it Is necessary to go into the 1\n^^^^^^mysterlous realm of finance and prob- I\n.?L- lill\ntRENT H\nraMK-w\nLTJB IN MADISON PLACE.\nibly then not come t>aek with any clear\ndea of what is the matter.\nQuestion of Money.\nThere is plenty of money, and then\nigain there is not, if that is underitandable.\nThe banks have large reierves,\nand the rate for loans has sunk\nray below the panic levels and are\ntack again to normal. There Is money\no be had for building, as the records\nnow wnere aeeas 01 trust axe piacea\nin file. But for some reason investnents\nof this sort are not In full tide,\n[\"here Is. however, more than was the\nase a few months ago. Residences are\nn the majority. Business places and\npartment houses are not as numerous\nmong the structures that are in proess\nof being built.\nThe reasons given for the statement\nhat building can be done more reasonbly\nat this time than wna the case, for\nnstance. last year are that materials\nost less and also that while there has\n>een no change In the scale of wagos\naid in the building trades yet, owing\no the slackness of work and the comletltlon\nfor Jobs, men are reported to be\nlolng a fuller day's work than was the\nase a year ago. Owing to this fact, the\nvork done roots up less in cost on mo\nvage account than formerly.\nThis condition of the market is unloubtedlv\ngoing to make itself felt\nnore and more as the season goes on,\nmd there is a probability that the\nisual course may be reversed and there\nnay be more buildings started later in\nhe season than during the early porlon.\nSurveyor's Office Busy.\nThe change that is going on in this repect\nis indicated in the course ot busless\nin the office of the District surveyor,\nrhere Mr. Richards finds that the appliations\nfor surveys of building lots are\nlore numerous than was the case last\near, and also that the volume of business\n5 greater than earlier in the season,\n'his last condition is unusual, for it is\nlore common that the rush for surveys\nn the part of those contemplating buildig\nis greater in the spring, and dwindles\ns summer approaches. Of course, all\nhe applications for the survey of lots\no not come from those who intend to\nuild. There are other reasons for seuring\nan official determination of the\nounds of land than that of iniproving it\nrlth building, but for the most part when\nsurvey of a lot is requested It generally\ns a preliminary to the erection of a\nuildlng.\nAt any rate the condition of business\nt this time in that office is significant\nit what is going on In the buildin gtrades.\nnd there is no doubt in the minds of\nhose familiar with the situation tnat the\noming months 'will witness an Increase\nat her than a decline in the operations\na this city.\nEnlarging Houses.\nChanges of importance are being made\na two of the residences in N street heween\n17th and 18th streets, which will\nesult In larger and more commodious\nernes. House 1751 N street, which was\necently purchased by Admiral Brownson,\ns being enlarged by the addition cn the\nast of a two-story and basement buildng.\nOn the first or main floor will be\nne large room, which will be a library,\nrhile above will be a bedroom. A lift Is\nelng put in, and a new staircase and\nther improvements. The architect is L>.\norris and the builder John 8. Larcombe.\nFrom plans made by the same architect\nhanges are also being made in the resiience\non the opposite side of the same\ntreet. which Mr. Morgan Hill recently\nfurchased. The main entrance is to be\n>n a level with the street, and a new\ntaircase is being provided\nThe addition to the building of the Cosnos\nClub, which extends its frontage on\niladison place south of H street, is to be\nemodeled so as to conform to the main\nlub building.\nrnis portion, onginany a private awenng.\nwas purchased some years ago by the\nluh. It is interesting to know on aeepunt\n>i the recent purchase of property by the\n>wner of the Arlington Hotel, adjoining\nhat building on H street, that the club\naid about >20 per square foot. This price\nvas said to have been given in the re ent\ntransaction by which the holdings of\nthe hotel were enlarged.\nNew Subdivision.\nWork has been begun on the grading\n>f the streets in the new subdivision ot\nRosemont. v. hich lies near Alexandria\nind along the line of the electric railway\noetween the two cities This enterprise\nnas been undertaken by men of means in\nthis city and Philadelphia, and according\nto the plans which they are preparing to\nfarry out the new town is to be provided\nwith all the conveniences for modsrn\nliving.\nSidewalks and gutters are to be put\nilown. and also sewers and water mains\nand next fall it is expected that at least\n100 trees will be set out. It is stated that\nno fences except hedge fences will be\npermitted. It ia also further announced\nthat the Rosemont Development Company\nlias given to contractors plans and specifications\nfor a number of attractive\nhouses, and in the very near future building\noperations will begun In earnest\nThe restrictions for the new suburb are\nsaid to be such as to eliminate ell objectionable\nfeatures and prevent any crowding.\nPlans for a railroad station to be\nlocated on the property have been prepared\nand the building is to be erected\nimmediately\nMount Pleasant Apartment.\nA local Investor has increased his rea:\nestate holdings by acquiring through\nStone Fairfax the brick and stone\napartment situate 1676 Irving street\nMount Pleasant. This building wai\nerected about three years ago for Mrs\nAPPENING\nSU# )!1 a n^HR\nLJ^BBP^WT ^^^fcfcJl|WBnit <BPyiB|BBHgEBi^wBfiBB^B^^^^r\nPsB|E 1\nMtf^L-, u rMB^;:;'i\nfll 0^^?m?i\ntrmw&M\nfflB\nflraaB?!LwlllMBH^MBBs9B?l&--S55Sl~;??~j*r^>BKl^\"\n|j?IhIi^^flU '^tlWvTlhi w'-i J-'*A' J v/v***\nWSBSfM^\nI Wp ^^(t^S^SBBBBSSffm^\nI ;<E?\nB w-^^-.?: ^|?|Sg\nLENMAN Bt\nCharlotte Dalley from plans drawn by A rj\nH. Beers, architect. The property will K\nbe held as an investment, as the building\nIs fully occupied by desirable tenants.\nBUILDING IS CHEAPER.\nComparison Between Present Prices\nand Those of. Last Year.\nFrom the American Lumberman. Ll\nLabor is cheaper now than it was a\nyear ago. although nominally wages are\nthe same. It is cheaper because it Is better.\nMaterials are cheaper than they were\na year ago. not for the same reason that\nlabor Is cheaper, but in the actual prices\nthat must be paid.\nin\nLast year the majority of the dealers in\nbuilding material had all the trade they\ncould hand'e. Tnis year business has been\nfair, as shown by the building records,\nbut there Is room for a very considerable u\nimprovement. al\nAs a general proposition lumber now is pi\nbeing sold for 10 to 15 per cent less than w\nduring last year. In some cases where\nthe trade Is supplied with special woods a\nreduction to that extent has not been tl:\nHnwpvfir 10 nor cent rrnhahlv rpp- ot\nresents about the general decline in the OJ\nretail price of building material.\nA Cleveland operator has supplied some\nspecific information showing the relative rc\ncost of building in 1W>7 and 1&0S which is rt\nreproduced herewith: st\nTer cent\nof dp1!K'7.\nIfiOR. creare.\nMasonry and grading. ...$1,329 $1>44 23.0 jn\nPlastering 585 31'1 t'S.8\nPlumbing ?40 -V>0 21 M hi\nHeatir.g \"30 J'} 22.U\nPainting 530 400 24 3\nLumber. $4 to thousand leea.\ncf\nThe foregoing comparative values rep-\nresent actual figures secured by a gentleman\nwho wished to build. The 1007 prices\nwere made during the latter part of that\nyear and the 100S prices this month.\nn<\nBiblical Archeology. w\nFrom the Jewish Chronicle.\nThe British Acedemy lectures by Dr. fr\nDriver on \"A'-cheological Research in hi\nRelation to Biblical Study\" will serve to st\ncall attention to the importance rf pick j*1\nand spade work for students of Bible f'\nhistory. It may safely be said that the f<work\naccomplished in this direction dur- i;<\nIng the past sixty years has added a v<\nfresh Interest to Scriptural studies, si\nThanks to the exhumation of content- fc\nporaneous records, we are enabled to ec\nread the ancient history of our race in b<\nI an entirely new light. w\ni 4ft\nvm\ni m\n\nRESIDENCE 07 H. C\n4\nrS IN TH\np I 1 SSEBBSaat\na I w, s* x* v\n.X*:*\nr-\nriLDING, RECENTLY SOLD FOB.\nEBUILO1NG SAN FRANCISCO^\nROGRESS OF RECONSTRUCTION\nSINCE THE QUAKE AND FIRE.\ntiger and Better Structures Have\nBeen. Erected in the Burned District?Population\nGrowing.\nTwo years have passed since the San\nranoisco disaster. On the 21st day of\npril, 1906, men looked at the smolderg\nruins left by a three days\" Are and\n>clared that the city would never be relilt;\nothers, more sanguine, thought\nherwise, but were sure It would take\niree years to clear away the debris\none, and it would be at least ten, and\n-obably fifteen, years before the city\nould bear even a faint resemblance to\ns former self. And those who made\niese predictions had no prescience of\nher calamities that were to follow hard\ni the heels of the areat catastronhe\nhieh had crumbled the city into ashes:\nr there were to follow bribery and coription\non the part of city officials,\nrikes, financial panic and a plague epismie.\nWith these things in mind it is almost\nipessible to believe the evidence of what\nis been done toward the reconstruction\nSan Francisco in the past two years\nhe fire of April 18, 19 and 20. 1906. dercyed\nS12 blocks of buildings, valued\n$103.C!)rt.OOO. Within the two years\nnee buildings to the value of $102,186.7\nhave been erected, or are being\neoted, within this burned area, and the\nluare feet of floor space is said to be\niw almost eoual to. if not in excess of,\nhat it was before the disaster. The\nitai number of buildings burned wes\n188, by far the larger number being\name or low brick structures. These\nive heen replaced by 14.270 modern\nructures. for the most part far better\nid larger than those destroyed. The\n>st and most accurate statistics on the\nibject are those gathered by the Callirnia\npromotion committee and pubrhed\nin bulletin form on the second anni?rsary\nof the disaster. This bulletin\nlows that within the past two years the\niliowing buildings have been construct1\nor are in course of construction, it\n?ing assumed that work has been begun\nlienevsr a building permit has been\n2 x dys. u ac.'ta: yMty.yx]\n'-v j\nI 'J$|\n\\\"A' I\nOBNELL WILSON IN 10TH STB\nfr\nE JREAL3\ni i^'mi'^TI i a ii ii ii--\n*N\n\nv: yrr' v .\\;j\nj. v.,.v '_>, j\n..v o\nr-y;\nX V; v:\\, f 'f\n\n..v N 'W\n\nv\nJ r\n^U\nV' r* 11 ?MtiMl\nI\nw?l\nI ^1 I\n^^^h^k^MMM^HjMMHflT v v.jj'i'i'^i B ?vM\n5 iiSmii UnHnB\n!F!fv:r; LTJHi\nM 1a3 *3 |3^ '^r *^JgK^?r\nhSH^b ||^H| BaBHUSn\nI\nfasmtmummmmmmmmoJp m\n$200,000.\ngranted: Sixty-three class \"A\" flreprool\nbuildings, valued at $16,452,000; ninetyfive\nreinforced concrete, brick or stone,\nwith steel floor beams, practically fireproof.\nvalued at $7,0864371; 1,907 concrete,\nbrick or stone, with wooden floor beams,\nvalued at $33,547,219 8.817 frame buildings.\nvalued at $37,139,694; changes and\nalterations to the number of 4.198 at a\nvalue of $8,010,933.\nLittle Outside Aid.\nPractically all of this work has beer\ndone without outside aid. the money, with\nthe exception of $3,000,000 or $4,000,000\nhaving been supplied by San Franciscc\ncapitalists and financial institutions; anc\nnotwithstanding this drain upon her resource!,,\na financial panic that affectec\nevery community in the country, laboi\ntroubles and graft, no San Francisco savings\nbank haR failed or shown the slightest\nelement of weakness. The only fail\nure of any moment was that of a trust\ncompany whose mismanagement was s<\nnagranny -dro ana aisnonest mat 11\nwould have failed in any event.\nNotwithstanding the enormous expenditure\nof money in rebuilding a city withir\nso short a time, San Francisco makes oni\nof the best showings of any city of th<\nfirst class in the United States in th?\npeicentage of mortgage indebtedness Ir\nrelation to the actual value of real es\ntate and improvements. In San Francisco\nthis percentage la 17. In Nerw Yorl\nit is 3b, in Philadelphia 54; in Pittsburg\n20, and in Cleveland, 27.\nBusiness and Population.\nAn idea of the volume of business trans\nacted by San Francisco is given in hei\nbank clearings, which for the year endec\nApril 18, 1007, were $2,006.885.508. Foi\nthe year ended April 18, 100S, the clearings\nwere $1.010,076.604. Eliminating th?\nnearly $200,000,000 of insurance mon?)\npail the preceding year, this would in\ndicate an increase the second year ol\nnearly $100,000,000.\nSan Francisco's population, which wai\nestimated at .100.000 before the Are. has\nalmost reached that point again. According\nto calQplations made Novem-bei\n1, 10O7, the population was then 479.S35\nAs it has been increasing steadily evet\nsince, it may now be safely estimated ai\nclose to what it was before the disaster\nThe four bay cities?San Francisco, Oak\nland, Berkeley and Alameda?have In\nci eased their population 130.000 withir\ntwo years, and the territory within t\nramus or nneen mups 01 me san f'ran\ncisco city hall is conservatively estimatet\nto have a population of 630,000. wit!\ngood reason to believe that It will pass\nthe million mark before the close of 1010\nSET NOBTHWEST.\n\n[T MARK]\nWfmmmm&**.\n*mm**mmt%K ^wy# ft\nI\nI\n-r \\rT\nBg?S=:Sa!a U\nBUILDING IN H STREET B.ECE\nHOTEL BT\nHOUSES J/VELL BUILT\nHigh Standard in Substantiality\nIs Maintained.\nAHEAD OF OTHER CITIES\nInfluence on the Market for Sale of\nBuildings.\nfi i\nHOME BUYERS ARE NUMEROUS\nRegulations Here Are More Stringent\nThan Elsewhere and Higher\nLevel Is Reached.\n?j\n\"The recent partial collapse of a building\nin course of erection in this city and\nthe accruing results tend to present a\nmisleading inference in some quarters\nas to the character and substantiality of\nstructures erected and in course of erection\nhere which should be corrected,\" a\nleading realty operator says.\n\"Whatever future amendments may be\nmade to the building regulations at present\nin force in the capital it should be\nunderstood that the public and prix-ate\nbuildings of Washington are as an entirety\nconstructed in the most substantial\nand solid manner, as compared with\nthose in other municipalities.\n\"This is well illustrated In many ways\nand especially by the fact that builders\nand speculators from other cities who\ncome to the capital with the intention of\nt erecting buildings for speculative purposes\nalong the lines to which they have\nbeen accustomed in their own homes And\nthat our building regulations are much\nmore stiff and rigorous than their own.\nTheir views as to the feasibility of rush\nup a 101 or cneap nouses nere ana\nselling them, as they have done elsewhere.\nundergo a change.\n\"While this may mean in one sense that\nbuildings here cost more relatively than\nIn some places, it also means that our\nstructures are better, are worth more\nmoney and are more substantially built\nthan the same class of buildings in many\ncities. As we are building for all time\nand not for expediency and quick sale,\nthis is one result which we desire to\nattain.\nA Superior Class of Homes.\n\"In substantiation of this fact the ex-1\nperience of a large building operator may\nbe cited with advantage. Having erected\nin the District over 600 houses of the\nmoderate-priced home class, he made a\ntour through the principal cities for the\nexpress object of comparing the operations\nin which he and other Washington\nfirms are engaged, as against those\nto be found elsewhere, giving to himself\na needed vacation at the same time.\n\"His observations and inspections were\nsuch that he was enabled to declare unequivocally\nthat, class for ciass and price\nfor price, the particular line of structures\nin which he and his associates were Interested\nin this city was much more\nsubstantial and superior to those he\nhad met with in the cities he visited.\n\"And It may be stated with equal positivc-ness\nthat this man's conclusion as to\nthe superior construction of our moderate-priced\nhome structures apply with\nequal force to all our buildings. The col\nlapse of a building under course of con-\netruction? in this city is such a rarity\ni that the single instance in question naturally\ncauses unusual comment\nj \"While there is no disposition on the\npart of realty operators or others to ex,\ncuse this instance or to attempt to mint-\nmite the deeply-to-be deplored results\nfollowing this unfortunate case, it is a\nfact nevertheless that this city has been\nremarkably fre om such distressing Instances.\nand they are. as is well known\nand the press reports show, of frequent\noccurrence elsewhere.\nSubstantial Construction.\n\"The fact that our homes are well built\nis one of several principal reasons why\nthey are in such demand and most of\nthem are sold substantially upon completion.\nand in very many instances before\nthey are roofed. The population of\nthe capital may he said to be a permanent\none. as contradistinguished from a\nplace where by reason of shifting commercial\nor manufacturing reasons there is\nmore or less change in the tenancy ar.d\noccupation of buildings, and such being\nthe case the buildings we erect are more\nsubstantial.\n\"There are a*, present in all quarters\nof the city, and particularly in the northwest.\nhundreds of these attractive and\nsubstantially built homes, recently completed\nand in course of construction. The\nfact that they are promptly sold and Immediately\noccupied, as well as bespoken\nfor in advance, is one of the most gn.i'C;\nIng phases of the realty market of the\nyear. It is not here as in many cities a\nquestion of And ng purchasers and tenants.\nbut rather' one of Anding the buildings\nthe rapidly augmenting colony of\nhome owners of the capital demands.\n\"Another reason why our buildings are\nj^.iy fn^Fnj I\nI\nx V 4.:_ I\nll I\n-Li.- t\nR|Q^H^^|^HK:u|^^B<pBW|i d^HH'\nI r.-aAr-\nf. III\nIII\n:ntly added to Arlington\nJILDING.\ni\nof the substantial quality is that they\nmay be said to follow in line with the\nSovcrnmem strui'iu.es ui me cuy- 1 new,\nas is well known, are hu'.lt In the most\nJ solid manntr, of the best materials and\n1 are in most instances veritable fortresses,\nj As regards individual business and ofiice\nbuildings those which have b?en recently\nerected in this city speak for themsel es.\nand are of a character which excite n\nmany or the mor.' o'.anh instances admiration\nupon vie-*.\n\"The same rule holds true with the individual\ndw liing as differentiating from\nthe dwellings erected In rows, to which\nI have preciously adverted. From the\npalaces in the northwest to the modest\nhomes in the northeast evidences of a\nhigher standard are visible to even the\ncasual observer. There is a noticeable\ntendency tc strive for better results in all\nclasses of structures, and with more\nrigid inspection and amended building\nregulations the fleld of building in the\ncapital may be said to offer brighter and\nmore attractive aspects than ever before.\nE\\'deuces of solidity.\n'indeed, it is one of the best evidences\nof our solidity and prosperity as a city to\nride through those sections of the capital\nin which bulldir.g is particularly active,\nand to note the sign 'Sold' tacked to the\nfront of houses yet uncompleted. In\nmany rows of homes this pleasing sign of\nthe times is often seen on a majority of\nthe houses under contract, and by the\ntime the contract Is completed and the\ncarpenter and plumber have removed\ni th?ir tools the remaining houses are llke!\nwise disposed of. In fact, the notice\n'For Rent' is so conspicuous by its absence\nas to cause comment on the part\nof the visitor and resident alike.\"\nTAFT AT YALE.\nOld Eli May Give the United States'\na President.\nFrom the Brooklyn Eagle.\nAmong the many tributes received by\nhim since his nomination at Chicago,\nnone, we believe, will be more grateful to\nMr. Taft than that which is his due from\nYale University. Yale holds him in affectionate\nesteem, regarding his achievements\nwith admiration and his future\nwith hope. For does he not promise to re\na. l *T TI_.... ?U\nmove IIom luc ^ew navcu iiiDiuui.'vn tiic\ninvidious distinction of never having given\na President to the United States?\nHarvard brought forth the Adamses and\nTheodore Roosevelt. Jefferson and Monroe\nwere sons of William and Mary,\nthough the latter was never graduated.\nPrinceton bred Madison. Polk's alma\nmater was the University of North Carolina.\nPierce came from Bowdoin, Buchani\nan from Dick nson. Hayes from Kenyon\nCollege. Gaffleld from Williams, Arthur\nfrom Union College. Benjamin Harrison\nfrom Miami and McKinley from Allegheny\nCollege. Washington. Van Buren, Jackson,\nWilliam Henry Harrison, Tyler. Taylor.\nFillmore, Lincoln, Johnson and Cleveland\nwere not college men. though Tyler\npassed through the grammar school of\nWilliam and Mary. Grant was the only\nWest Point man to become President,\nthough Hancock and McClellan were candidates\nfor the office.\nTAPEWORMS.\nHad Long Puzzled Scientists Until'\nVon Siebold Discovered Source.\nFrom Everybody's.\nA German named Von Siebold made\nhimself a specialist on tapeworms, and in\nthe course of his researches discovered\nthat cats and owls were infested with\nexactly the same kind of tapeworms. He\ntlien cogitated on what the bird and the\ncat could possibly have In common, and\nconcluded that It could be only In the\nsingle matter of diet, namely, that both\nare mice. He proceeded then to investigate\nmice, and found In some of them not\ntapeworms, but a great number of minute\nbag-shaped creatures now called cystlcerci.\nwhich had burrowed into their\nflesh. These had little resemblance as\npossible to tapeworms, which may be\niwpntv feet lonff. He then fed the meat\nof such unfortunate mice to dogs, pigs\ni and chickens, and In due time, lo! ail\nthree grew the same tapeworms with\nthose of cats and owls. The commonest\nkind among our tapeworms comes from\neating beef not sufficiently cooked to kill\nthe cyticerci In It.\n1 1 f\nThe Hudson Palisades.\nfrom Hxrper's Msffxiine.\nThe edge of the world, if such a thing\nmay be. lies hardly a rifle shot away from\none of the centers of the world itself?the\ncity of New York.\nThe Palisades, those mighty walls\nwhereon the annals of the centuries are\ngraved?what an edge of the world their\nlip presents to him who comes, perhaps\nat night, to their rough-hewn elevation!\nIn no place other than this near proximity\nto nr.an ar.i one cf his greatest cities\ncould a physical feature so profoundly\nvast and impressive be so hidden from\nthe world. Tneir counterpart cannot be\nfound in all the world; and yet the Palisades\nare almost unexplolted ana unknown\nto the globe-circling, sight-hunting public\nthat >earl} traverses the continents or\nseas to gaze at things less wonderful in\nsome distant field of nature's marvelous\nachievements. For little does any or.a\nknow of these Titanic walls who has\nmerely seen them from the Hudson. Were\nthey somewhere off in a land comparatively\n.inaccessible. reached by a transcontinental\nthread of steel, the guide books\nwould be rich In their pictured gandeur\nand man would rove far to explore iheak","height":"38040","width":"27152"}}
